    <item>
      <title>Towers of Midnight</title>
      <link>https://blog.jverkamp.com/2018/09/04/towers-of-midnight/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 04 Sep 2018 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      
      <guid>https://blog.jverkamp.com/2018/09/04/towers-of-midnight/</guid>
      <description>&lt;figure class=&#34;cover-image&#34;&gt;
                &lt;a data-goodreads-type=&#34;book&#34; data-goodreads-id=&#34;8253920&#34; href=&#34;https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/8253920.towers-of-midnight&#34;&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;https://blog.jverkamp.com/embeds/books/towers-of-midnight.jpg&#34;&gt;
                &lt;/a&gt;
            &lt;/figure&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a data-goodreads-type=&#34;book&#34; data-goodreads-id=&#34;8253920&#34; href=&#34;https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/8253920.towers-of-midnight&#34;&gt;Towers of Midnight&lt;/a&gt; continues the final avalanche to the Last Battle, with Lan continuing to gathering followers, the Black Tower continuing to grow more and more corrupt, Perrin confronting the Whitecloaks (it&amp;rsquo;s about time that storyline wraps up), and the newly healed Rand causing even more chaos than before.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Many people, when asked what they notice most about the change from Jordan&amp;rsquo;s writing to Sanderson&amp;rsquo;s mention that Mat is different. Honestly, I didn&amp;rsquo;t really notice it. I like Mat&amp;ndash;Mat in all his guises. Poisoned by the dagger. Helping his friends no matter what. Son of Battle, Prince of the Ravens. He&amp;rsquo;s one of my favorite characters. If he feels different under Sanderson, it almost feels like growing up. After all:&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    
